body:
When processing Verilog file with Yosys 0.7+658 (git sha1 12440fc, gcc 6.2.1 -fPIC -Os):

```
module bidirtest (
A, EO, Q, BI
);

inout BI;
output Q;
input A;
input EO;

assign BI = (EO == 1'b1) ? A : 1'bz;
assign Q = BI;

endmodule 

```
with script

```
read_verilog bidirtest.v
tribuf -logic
synth -top bidirtest
iopadmap -bits -inpad IBUF O:PAD -outpad OBUF I:PAD -tinoutpad IOBUF ENA:O:I:PAD bidirtest
write_verilog -noattr proj_iotemp.v

```
it produces Verilog file
```

/* Generated by Yosys 0.7+658 (git sha1 12440fc, gcc 6.2.1 -fPIC -Os) */

module bidirtest(A, EO, Q, BI);
  wire _0_;
  wire _1_;
  wire _2_;
  wire _3_;
  input A;
  inout BI;
  input EO;
  output Q;
  IOBUF _4_ (
    .ENA(_2_),
    .I(_1_),
    .O(_0_),
    .PAD(BI)
  );
  IBUF _5_ (
    .O(_1_),
    .PAD(A)
  );
  IBUF _6_ (
    .O(_2_),
    .PAD(EO)
  );
  OBUF _7_ (
    .I(_3_),
    .PAD(Q)
  );
  assign _3_ = BI;
endmodule

```
.

In command line when inserting IO buffers YOSYS says that it first substitutes bidirectional IO, then inputs and outputs:

```
4. Executing IOPADMAP pass (mapping inputs/outputs to IO-PAD cells).
Mapping port bidirtest.BI[0] using IOBUF.
Mapping port bidirtest.A using IBUF.
Mapping port bidirtest.EO using IBUF.
Mapping port bidirtest.Q using OBUF.

```
When inserting IO cells into module YOSYS fails to detect that bidirections port's output net changed to another and still follows assignment operator(Q = BI).
Is it the correct operation mode or should YOSYS detect bidirectional port's usage in other parts and substitute it with net connected to output port of inout buffer?
If it is correct operation mode, then insertion of IO buffers doesn't make sense anymore, because PAD signal is now directly connected to internal parts.

